        <h1 id="About">A Generative Journey </h1> <!--Add padding-->
            <p>When you look around society at large you'll find that most people are specialists who do one thing well. In fact, society incentivises and rewards such behaviour, which in turn shapes the behaviour of people in its image. <strong> I'm not one of those people. </strong> </p> 
            <p> For whatever reason, I've never been satisfied doing "just one thing" and have a drive to transcend disciplines while including new skills. Such people are often called "polymaths", "generalists", "multipotentiates", "pantologists" or more simply "renaissance people". We're a minority in what seems like a sea of madness but historically the most curious cats out there seem to fall into these categories; Plato, Pythagoras, DaVinci, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hrcJz63En94&list=PLANorT3Y7McMKzxqTw8u8ykq3pe_6A0Tn"> Maynard James Keenen</a>, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KdnGPQaICjk">Ted Nelson</a>, <a href="https://www.dgmlive.com/in-depth/the-guitar-circle-book-table-of-contents">Robert Fripp (King Crimson)</a>, Steve Jobs and Sylvain Richard (20syl). </p>
            
            <p> <h3>This is my personal story, scroll to the bottom for a list of links! </h3> </p>
            
            <p>The first skill I remember getting reasonably good at was the guitar, however its also the speciality I'm probably least proficient in as I learnt without any particular framework or discipline! It was a practice that led to related endeavours like building a replica Gibson Les Paul and dabbling with home recording... Guitar building was a one time passion project but home recording eventually led to a <strong> Masters degree in Audio Technology</strong>.</p>
            <p> <strong>Heres a picture of said guitar and a video of me performing some material I wrote: </strong></p>
            <div class="flex justify-center grid-cols-2 gap-12 bg-primary-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4"> <!-- Justify centre is the closes to what I want but not evenly spaced -->
