            </div>
            <p>As mentioned, playing the guitar opened up many doors; like many teenagers I was into rock music and I started out on an electric guitar but as my tastes matured I started to enjoy playing an acoustic. Not wishing to limit myself I started to pick up a cornicopia of other instruments; drums, bass, mandolin, harmonica, didgeredoo and just about anything else physically available to me. </p>
            <p>En route to a masters in Audio I took a detour through the circus arts, dance and object manipulation... which along with board sports helped hone my physical dexterity and coordination. Juggling's in itself is super interesting and has its own symbol language called <a href="http://www.twjc.co.uk/jugglingnotations.html">siteswap</a> to describe types of throws! (as exhibited in some of the verrry old shots below - circa age 18)</p>
            
            <div class="flex justify-center grid-cols-2 gap-12 bg-primary-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
              <div> <iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/dpC7pGyaLLg" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe> </div>
            </div>
            <p>This brings us up to the point of leaving school... At this point, the garden of forking paths could have gone many directions but upon finishing I decided to take a year out, earn some cash to buy recording equipment to set myself up for more serious study over the next few years. This was a top of the range Mackbook Pro and a Digidesign 002 desk that I got second hand from my friends dad who was professional musician. </p>
            <p>Somewhere over this stint, myself and a peer volunteered to do some live sound at a music festival and ended up running a small tent with no scheduled acts... so we took on stage management duties and ended up recruiting anyone we saw moving between stages with instruments! While scouring the waterlogged planes of the ironically names "Solace" festival we stumbled upon a local Cork band called Neon Flea Circus and invited them to play, they obliged with a blistering gig and we offered to record them. This project took on a life of its own across a variety of locations and with whatever equipment we could cobble together we recorded a creative commons album that <strong>absolutely bloody rocked!!</strong></p>
            <p>Given we were releasing the art for free, I got very interested in the commerce aspect of music marketing and decided to do the album promotion for a final year project (along with recordings from another band we also met at Solace named "Sons of Gingerbread"). Surprisingly we did manage to turn a buck from releasing a free album in conjunction with a national tour and merchandise. For these efforts I graduated with a 1:1, and earned myself a scholarship to do a masters degree at the same university which took two years part-time. </p>

            <div class="flex rounded-lg"> <!-- Works locally but not on Netlify-->
              <iframe class="flex rounded-lg mb-6" width="1150" height="678" src="http://neonfleacircus.com/download/index.php"></iframe> <!--why flex no work-->
            </div>

            <p>During this period I spent time investigating how we subjectivly interpret sound and the driving question of "what is music?". This initiative started by prototyping 'musical' distortion units in a program called MaxMSP, which I used to track and manipulate fundemental frequencies. Surround sound recording techniques also caught my attention; I wanted to know "how do we capture the sound of physical enviroments and reproduce such richness in our living rooms?". To find out, I experimented with a number of techniques leveraging <i> head related transfer functions</i>: <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binaural_recording">binaural heads</a>, <a href="https://lossenderosstudio.com/article.php?subject=17">hamasaki squares and optimised cardioid triangles</a> to be precise. All just different models for mapping the terrain in various ways. </p> 
            <p>Eventually my research cumulated in the question of "why do we tend to prefer the aesthetic qualities of certain sounds over others?" and namely I focused on the age old debate of analogue vs digital (specifically tubes vs transistors) which eventually surfaced the inherent laws of vibration; precicely what pythogoras meant when he proclaimed "the octave never repeats". In this case it turned out that tubes produce second (rather than third) order harmonic distortion, leading to intermodulation frequencies (sum and difference) and giving rise to the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pythagorean_tuning">pythagorean mucical scale</a> at smaller and smaller fractal dimensions! </p>
            
            <div class="flex justify-center grid-cols-2 bg-primary-200 rounded-lg p-4 mb-4">
              <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/19152308" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
              <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/108854060" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen" allowfullscreen></iframe>
            </div>

            <p>Having polished other peoples music for several years, I decided to get self indulgent for my masters project by writing and recording a concept album in 5.1 surround sound. The production turned out pretty well (lyrics, songwriting, musicianship and recording), though to be perfectly honest it wasn't as life affirming as the Fleas stuff I'd previously poured my heart and soul into - it had slightly less character from the more sterile "professional" spaces which I feel reduced its dimensionality, even if the sonic depth was of higher fidelity. Still it scratched an itch for self expression and I got to wear many hats!</p>
            <div>
              <iframe class="mb-4" width="100%" height="350" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" allow="autoplay" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/playlists/1147256257%3Fsecret_token%3Ds-wDjI70jMrZY&color=%237c6854&auto_play=false&hide_related=false&show_comments=true&show_user=true&show_reposts=false&show_teaser=true"></iframe>
            </div>

            <p>Post education I enetered into the arena of live sound, at first part time in <a href="https://barnightjar.com/">Bar Nightjar</a> which was a small but fun jazz bar, and then filled out my time with other freelance gigs such as quality control for DVD & BluRay at <a href="https://www.thisismetropolis.com/">Metropolis Chiswick</a>. After this things broadened into running lights, sound and media centers for a hotel chain in Portugal which was unfulfilling but paid the bills. </p> 
            <p>Upon return to the UK I leveraged this experience and got a position as Technical Manager for Shoreditch Bar Group, a dysfunctional organisation responsible for the serfdom of Shoreditch but a playground of broken systems scattered around a local radius. I learnt quite a lot in this enviroment of scarcity like programming ShowCAD or how to fix lights, while picking up various electric and electronic repair tricks (as well as a few shocks and scars). </p> 
            <p>At some stage though I'd had enough of Shoreditch serfdom and decided to form my own company with some other technical managers I got to know from around other venues. Things started to look up as I got contracted by my old employer at Bar Nighjar to build their sister venues <a href="https://www.oriolebar.com/">Oriole's</a> stage and sound system, which would be used for live jazz seven days a week. The next bits of luck were other venue comissions for a high end bar/resturant in Monument called <a href="https://www.mber.london/">Mber</a> and another called in Soho called <a href="https://www.barswift.com/">Swift</a>.</p>
            
